    • lock

      public void lock()
      Description copied from interface: Type
      Locks this Type, making it immutable. Note that this does not necessarily lock the child Types of compound types such as TypeAnd. Since Type hierarchies can contain circular references, it may be necessary to instantiate Types, build their values, and then lock them to maintain immutability.
      Specified by:
      lock in interface Type

    • forEach

      public void forEach(Consumer<TypeConcrete> consumer, Set<TypeConcrete> seen)
      Description copied from interface: TypeConcrete
      Applies a consumer function over this Type and its child Types, if any. This method does not walk the entire Type tree. Specifically, TypeParameterized will not apply the consumer to its corresponding TypeDeclaration. However, this method will apply the consumer to each TypeParameter and its bounds (unlike TypeConcrete.map(Function)). To prevent recursion if the bounds are circular, a Set containing the visited types is passed to this function and each child invocation of the function, ensuring any instance of a type is visited only once.

      Note that this method is primarily called within the TypeConcrete.forEach(Consumer, Set) implementation to pass the visited type set to children Types. For general purpose use, TypeConcrete.forEach(Consumer) should be used.

      Specified by:
      forEach in interface TypeConcrete
      Parameters:
      consumer - The action to apply to each TypeConcrete
      seen - The set of types already visited
      See Also:
      • TypeConcrete.forEach(Consumer)

    • equalsExactly

      public boolean equalsExactly(TypeConcrete other)
      Description copied from interface: TypeConcrete
      Checks if this TypeConcrete is exactly equal to another TypeConcrete. This requires the same type structure, whereas the normal Object.equals(Object) method on TypeConcretes checks for type equality (e.g., a TypeAnd with one element is considered equal to any type which is equal to that element).
      Specified by:
      equalsExactly in interface TypeConcrete
      Parameters:
      other - The other TypeConcrete to check equality against
      Returns:
      True if the this is exactly structurally equal to other
